<p>1. If you can just lock it in a box somewhere, not mess with it, and have nothing happen, then it should be Safe, not Euclid. Euclid means that if you lock something in a box and leave it alone, then there's no telling what will happen.</p>
<p>2. As it is, it seems too predictable and tidy. You perform a function, it does exactly as programmed every time. That's… not realistic for any Win95 system, much less one modified to SCP specifications. I'd expect more blue screens and general protection faults and illegal operations, with all the attendant consequences. (It would also make it more dangerous to use and could possibly earn it its Euclid class.)</p>
<p>3. The picture has speakers, which contradicts the description of having only mouse, keyboard, and monitor. There's also no mention of CD-Rom or floppy drives, but that's a minor point.</p>
<p>('Course, since it's about to hit double digits, the feedback may be moot anyway.)</p>

